  <!-- What's actually going on -->
  <div class="py-20">
    <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-primary mb-4">What's Actually Happening</p>
    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-foreground mb-6">Your brain learned to be awake at night. We can unteach it.</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>Chronic insomnia is almost never just about sleep. It starts with stress, a health scare, or a life change, and then something shifts. Your brain starts associating your bed with wakefulness and anxiety instead of rest. The harder you try to sleep, the more alert your nervous system becomes. It becomes a loop you can't break on your own.</p>
      <p>The tips that work for normal sleepers stop working for you because the problem isn't your habits anymore. It's the association your brain has built between night and threat. That is not a character flaw. It is a conditioned response, and it responds to a very specific kind of treatment.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

